what: Analyze Sequence Diversity Of Gene Families
title: Analyze Sequence Diversity Of Gene Families
text: purpose dgfr package enable visualization sequence diversity within gene/protein families. addition, also possible determine optimal number clusters grouping members gene families based sequence similarity calculate mean/median similarity inside cluster.

title: Analyze Sequence Diversity Of Gene Families
text: proceeding installation dgfr package, must install following dependencies: Now can install dgfr package using following command:
code: if (!requireNamespace("BiocManager", quietly = TRUE)) {     install.packages("BiocManager") } BiocManager::install("Biostrings", dependencies = TRUE) # install.packages("devtools") # devtools::install_github("lailaviana/dgfr") library(dgfr)

title: Analyze Sequence Diversity Of Gene Families
text: First, retrieve FASTA sequences gene family studied database choice. fasta file must loaded inside R using Biostrings::readAAStringSet() case protein sequences Biostrings::readDNAStringSet() case nucleotide sequences. prefer, can utilize sample dataset included package named fasta, comprises 75 protein sequences. instance, employ complete set proteins tcmuc_fasta. object containing fasta provided first function named get_alignment_score, also provide type o sequence “nuc” nucleotide “prot” protein, alignment method (“global” “local”) number cores used analysis. score calculated using following formula: algn_seq1seq2 / (sqrt(algn_seq1seq1) * sqrt(algn_seq2seq2)) formula first proposed Bleakley Yamanashi way normalize score length alignment. output dataframe containing score pairwise alignment among sequences provided. output first function package, provided second function called create_distance_matrix. function calculates average Euclidian distance score pairwise alignment. generating distance matrix, use get_variance function access variability explained axis. requires provision file containing distance matrix. general, cumulative value 70% higher axis considered adequate explaining data’s variance. subsequent required step consists multidimensional scaling (MDS) data matrix. output consist name sequence position axes 1 2. possible functionality dgfr package determine optimal number clusters dataset. must provide dimension-reduced file , desired, minimum maximum number clusters identified. provide values, script automatically search 2 20 clusters. Finally, table containing name sequence, position axes 1 2, cluster sequence belongs. next function, allows visualize sequences cluster tree-like structure. must provide kmeans_clustering function output create_distance_matrix output. output plot containing sequences cluster.  Finally, can access mean/median similarity among cluster using function similarity_cluster. function takes argument kmeans_clustering function output, get_alignment_score output must also choose two possible visualizations output. “table” output returns table containing mean median similarity among clusters number genes inside cluster. “plot” output returns plot containing violin plot highlighting distribution similarity within cluster.
code: tcmuc_fasta <- Biostrings::readAAStringSet("data-raw/tcmuc_fasta") score_file <- dgfr::get_alignment_score(fasta = tcmuc_fasta,                                         type = "prot",                                         alignment_method = "global",                                         cores = 4) #> [1/6] Loading substitution matrix... #> [2/6] Loading fasta file... #> [3/6] Creating all possible sequence combinations... #> [4/6] Performing pairwise alignment for prot sequences. This might take a while... #> [5/6] Finishing up... #> [6/6] Pairwise alignment is done. distance_matrix <- dgfr::create_distance_matrix(score_file = score_file) variance <- dgfr::get_variance(distance_matrix = distance_matrix) variance |> dplyr::select(1:3) #> # A tibble: 1 × 3 #>     `1`   `2`   `3` #>   <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> #> 1  81.7  10.5  3.34 dim_reduced_file <- dgfr::dim_reduction(distance_matrix = distance_matrix) head(dim_reduced_file) #>                          axis_1     axis_2 #> TcYC6_0150500-RA-p1  0.01410299 0.08506485 #> TcYC6_0150510-RA-p1 -1.10954550 0.30707240 #> TcYC6_0150520-RA-p1 -0.97152461 0.20716940 #> TcYC6_0150530-RA-p1 -1.13936354 0.29036688 #> TcYC6_0150540-RA-p1 -0.73347654 0.01002143 #> TcYC6_0150550-RA-p1  0.43034170 0.19684138 kmeans_output <- dgfr::kmeans_clustering(dim_reduced_file = dim_reduced_file) head(kmeans_output) #>                  name      axis_1     axis_2 cluster #> 1 TcYC6_0150500-RA-p1  0.01410299 0.08506485       1 #> 2 TcYC6_0150510-RA-p1 -1.10954550 0.30707240       1 #> 3 TcYC6_0150520-RA-p1 -0.97152461 0.20716940       1 #> 4 TcYC6_0150530-RA-p1 -1.13936354 0.29036688       1 #> 5 TcYC6_0150540-RA-p1 -0.73347654 0.01002143       1 #> 6 TcYC6_0150550-RA-p1  0.43034170 0.19684138       1 tree <- dgfr::create_tree(distance_matrix = distance_matrix,                 kmeans_output = kmeans_output)  tree dgfr::similarity_cluster(score_file = score_file,                          kmeans_output = kmeans_output,                          output_type = "table") #> # A tibble: 3 × 4 #>   cluster   mean_similarity median_similarity number_of_genes #>   <chr>               <dbl>             <dbl>           <int> #> 1 cluster_1           0.509             0.503             391 #> 2 cluster_2           0.756             0.707              49 #> 3 cluster_3           0.434             0.260              36 dgfr::similarity_cluster(score_file = score_file,                          kmeans_output = kmeans_output,                          output_type = "plot")

title: Analyze Sequence Diversity Of Gene Families
text: visualization suggestions presented created using ggplot2 package. However, allowed use preferred package tool visualize obtained data.

title: Analyze Sequence Diversity Of Gene Families
text: simplest form visualization scatter plot sequences particular gene family, point represents sequence, distance two points proportional similarity sequences.
code: kmeans_output |>    ggplot2::ggplot(     ggplot2::aes(x = axis_1,                   y = axis_2)) +    ggplot2::geom_point(size = 3.5, alpha = 0.3) +   ggplot2::theme_bw() +   ggplot2::labs(x = round(variance$`1`, 2),                  y = round(variance$`2`, 2))

what: Identifying particular sequences within the gene family
title: Analyze Sequence Diversity Of Gene Families
text: second suggested plot similar first, allows highlighting sequences interest. addition ggplot2, gghighlight ggrepel required perform analysis.
code: seq_name <- kmeans_output |>    dplyr::sample_n(5) |>    dplyr::select(name) |>    dplyr::pull()  kmeans_output |>    ggplot2::ggplot(     ggplot2::aes(x = axis_1,                   y = axis_2)) +    ggplot2::geom_point(size = 3.5, alpha = 0.3) +   ggplot2::theme_bw() +   ggplot2::labs(x = round(variance$`1`, 2),                  y = round(variance$`2`, 2)) + gghighlight::gghighlight(name %in% seq_name) +    ggrepel::geom_text_repel(label = seq_name,                             min.segment.length = 0,                             seed = 42,                             box.padding = 0.5)

what: Identifying the number of clusters within the gene family
title: Analyze Sequence Diversity Of Gene Families
text: third visualization suggestion, gene family divided optimal number groups, represented different color.
code: kmeans_output |>    dplyr::mutate(cluster = as.character(cluster)) |>    ggplot2::ggplot(     ggplot2::aes(x = axis_1,                   y = axis_2,                  color = cluster)) +    ggplot2::geom_point(size = 3.5, alpha = 0.3) +   ggplot2::theme_bw() +   ggplot2::labs(x = round(variance$`1`, 2),                  y = round(variance$`2`, 2))

title: Analyze Sequence Diversity Of Gene Families
text: Another functionality integrate RNAseq data visualize expression dispersion gene family scatter plot. size points proportional gene expression level family member, small points representing genes low expression large points representing genes high expression.
code: kmeans_out_l2fc <- kmeans_output |>    dplyr::mutate(l2fc = runif(476, min = 0.1, max = 4))  kmeans_out_l2fc |>    dplyr::mutate(cluster = as.character(cluster)) |>    ggplot2::ggplot(     ggplot2::aes(x = axis_1,                   y = axis_2,                  color = cluster)) +    ggplot2::geom_point(size = kmeans_out_l2fc$l2fc, alpha = 0.3) +   ggplot2::theme_bw() +   ggplot2::labs(x = round(variance$`1`, 2),                  y = round(variance$`2`, 2))
